    "instruction": "From metric.csv, restrict rows to cmdb_id in [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute: count, global P95 of value, min(timestamp) and max(timestamp). Return the top 20 groups ordered by count. Provide columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p95_value, min_timestamp, max_timestamp. Limit output to these 20 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global P95 thresholds for (cmdb_id, kpi_name) groups across the allowed root-cause components using the full available metric series. The top-20 groups shown are uniformly sampled across the 30-minute window and Tomcat04 appears frequently among high-P95 KPIs (thread counts, request error counts, processing time). Error logs are concentrated between 14:20:09 and 14:26:50 and are mostly from Tomcat nodes (Tomcat03/04/02/01), which aligns with metric suspects. To follow the workflow we must now perform anomaly detection within the incident time window (2021-03-24 14:00 → 14:30 UTC+8) by finding metric points that exceed the global P95 thresholds. This will narrow down which component-KPIs actually had abnormal activity during the incident window and provide earliest anomaly timestamps for fault identification.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the global P95 values already computed per (cmdb_id, kpi_name), filter metric.csv to rows where cmdb_id is one of [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02] and timestamp within 2021-03-24 14:00:00 → 2021-03-24 14:30:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute: (1) anomaly_count = number of rows with value >= p95_value, (2) earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8) among those rows, (3) max_value within the 30-min window, (4) p95_value, and (5) max_over_p95 = max_value / p95_value (if p95_value==0 set max_over_p95 to NULL or a special marker). Return the top 20 groups ordered by anomaly_count descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value, p95_value, max_over_p95. Limit output to 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 thresholds for component-KPIs using the full metric series, then flagged metric points in the 14:00–14:30 window that exceeded those P95 thresholds. The top flagged groups show many Tomcat and IG JVM KPIs with anomaly_count == 31 (every minute), and many groups have p95_value == max_value (max_over_p95 == 1.0). This pattern can indicate either consistently-high-but-normalized metrics or thresholds of zero for some KPIs, so it doesn't yet unambiguously point to a single fault. Separately, error_logs are concentrated between 14:20:09 and 14:26:50 and are predominantly from Tomcat nodes (Tomcat03/04/02/01), which suggests the actual failure incident likely occurred in that ~14:20–14:27 sub-window and involved Tomcat instances. To localize the root cause component we should aggregate the anomaly results by component to see which component(s) have the most and most-severe KPI faults and the earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Aggregate the anomaly detection results (the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) table you computed) by cmdb_id. For each cmdb_id compute: (1) sum_anomaly_count (sum of anomaly_count across KPIs), (2) num_kpis_flagged (count of distinct kpi_name with anomaly_count>0), (3) earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min of earliest_anomaly_timestamp across its KPIs, UTC+8), (4) peak_severity = max(max_over_p95) among its KPIs (ignore NaN), and (5) top_3_kpis = comma-separated list of up to 3 kpi_name values ranked by anomaly_count (desc) then by max_over_p95 (desc). Return rows ordered by sum_anomaly_count descending, limit to top 20 rows, with columns: cmdb_id, sum_anomaly_count, num_kpis_flagged, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, peak_severity, top_3_kpis." }

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated per-(component,KPI) anomalies and summarized by component. Findings: Mysql01/Mysql02 have the largest number of flagged KPIs (broad, many low-severity anomalies across many KPIs) with earliest anomalies at the very start of the 30-min window (14:00). Several Tomcat nodes (Tomcat01–04) show fewer but higher-severity KPI spikes (peak_severity > 3), and error_logs are concentrated between 14:20:09 and 14:26:50 coming from Tomcat03/04/02/01. This pattern suggests two possibilities: (A) a widespread baseline shift across many DB/infra KPIs (MySQL/Redis) present throughout the window, or (B) a more targeted, higher-severity problem impacting Tomcat instances around 14:20–14:26 that generated error logs. To decide which is the root cause we must use traces to determine service-level call chains and locate the most-downstream faulty service. Per the workflow, next is trace analysis: compute global thresholds for trace features and detect which trace features (per component) breached thresholds during the incident window, and when their earliest breaches occurred. This will help identify downstream faulty services and align traces with Tomcat error log times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, restrict to cmdb_id in [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 of value using the full available series. Then filter trace.csv to timestamps within 2021-03-24 14:00:00 → 2021-03-24 14:30:00 (UTC+8) and count anomaly rows where value >= P95 for the corresponding (cmdb_id, trace_name). For each group report: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8), max_value (30-min window), p95_value, max_over_p95 (max_value / p95_value; if p95==0 set to NULL). Return top 20 groups ordered by anomaly_count desc. Limit output to these 20 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran metric and trace anomaly detection and aggregated results by component. Key findings so far: (1) Trace anomalies (trace.duration_p95) show clear spikes around 14:20:00 (UTC+8) — several duration_p95 traces hit ~60s on IG02, MG01 and Tomcat04-related flows, and multiple trace groups have earliest anomalies at 2021-03-24T14:20:00+08:00. (2) Metrics show many MySQL/Redis KPIs flagged across the whole 14:00–14:30 window (broad, low-to-moderate severity anomalies starting at 14:00), while several Tomcat nodes show fewer but high-severity spikes (peak_severity > 3). (3) error_logs.csv entries are concentrated between 14:20:09 and 14:26:50 and predominantly come from Tomcat nodes (Tomcat03/04/02/01) — this aligns temporally with the trace duration spikes. Combined, these suggest the incident likely manifested as downstream request timeouts/latency around ~14:20 impacting Tomcat services (generating error logs), while DB/infra anomalies existed more broadly and may be secondary or background noise. To confirm the exact root-cause component and occurrence time we must inspect error log distribution and the normalized log.error_count series (to get precise earliest error timestamps and which Tomcat instance first logged errors).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From error_logs.csv, filter rows to timestamps within 2021-03-24 14:00:00 → 2021-03-24 14:30:00 (UTC+8). Group by cmdb_id and compute: count, earliest timestamp, latest timestamp. Return top 10 cmdb_ids ordered by count. Also for the top 3 cmdb_ids, return up to 5 distinct sample messages each with their earliest message timestamp (limit messages to 5 per cmdb_id).\n2) From log.csv, filter rows to the same time window and to rows where log_name == 'log.error_count' and value > 0. Return up to 50 rows sorted by timestamp with columns: timestamp (UTC+8), cmdb_id, log_name, value. \n(Keep outputs compact and bounded as requested.)"
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global P95 thresholds, detected metric anomalies across components, aggregated anomalies by component, analyzed traces for duration/row_count spikes, and inspected logs and error_logs. Findings so far: (1) Metric anomalies are widespread (Mysql/Redis show many flagged KPIs throughout 14:00–14:30), but several Tomcat instances show high-severity metric spikes. (2) Trace anomalies (notably duration_p95) concentrate at ~14:20:00 UTC+8 and indicate long downstream latencies/timeouts (many duration_p95 ≈ 60s) on paths involving IG and MG and Tomcat services. (3) error_logs are concentrated 14:21:20→14:26:50 and are dominated by Tomcat instances; log.error_count spikes most dramatically at 14:26 for multiple Tomcats. (4) Per-Tomcat summary shows earliest_trace_anomaly times: Tomcat01=14:01, Tomcat02=14:12, Tomcat03=14:12, Tomcat04=14:12; earliest_error_log times: Tomcat02=14:21:20 (earliest among Tomcats), Tomcat03=14:22:07, Tomcat04=14:22:52, Tomcat01=14:26:39. Interpretation: trace duration spikes start around 14:20 and error logs begin shortly after (14:21+), with Tomcat02 being the first Tomcat to log errors. According to the localization rules, the root cause for a single failure is the most-downstream faulty service in the trace call chain. We need to confirm which Tomcat was the most-downstream service showing trace anomalies earliest in the critical ~14:20 window to reliably pick the root-cause component and exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, filter rows where timestamp is within 2021-03-24 14:15:00 → 2021-03-24 14:24:00 (UTC+8) and where either: (A) trace_name contains 'to_Tomcat02' or 'to_Tomcat03' or 'to_Tomcat04', OR (B) cmdb_id is one of [Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04] and trace_name starts with 'trace.self'. Using the previously computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name), identify anomaly rows where value >= P95. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group return: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count (within this filter), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8), max_value, p95_value, max_over_p95. Order results by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending and limit to top 20 rows. Keep output compact." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow so far: computed global thresholds, detected metric anomalies across components, aggregated by component, examined traces, and inspected logs. Key findings: (1) Trace duration spikes begin around 14:20:00 UTC+8 (many duration_p95 ≈ 60s on IG/MG/Tomcat paths). (2) Metric anomalies are broad (MySQL/Redis) across the whole window, but several Tomcat instances show high-severity spikes. (3) Error logs are concentrated 14:21:20→14:26:50 and are dominated by Tomcat instances; Tomcat02 is the first Tomcat to produce an error log (earliest_error_log=2021-03-24T14:21:20+08:00) and Tomcat02 also shows an early, large trace.self.duration_mean anomaly at 2021-03-24T14:20:00+08:00 with high severity (max_over_p95 ≈ 2.8). Tomcat03 and Tomcat04 also show elevated durations slightly later (≈14:22). According to the localization rules, the root cause is typically the most-downstream faulty service that first exhibits a significant deviation. The evidence points to Tomcat02 as the earliest downstream service with severe duration anomalies followed by the earliest Tomcat error logs. To confirm the exact root cause reason (resource-level cause: high CPU, memory, JVM OOM, or backend DB latency), we need to inspect Tomcat02's metric KPIs in the critical interval (focused around 14:15–14:24) and find resource KPIs with large (>50%) breaches of global P95. This will let us determine whether the cause is e.g., high CPU, JVM GC/heap issues, or backend DB latency.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, focus on cmdb_id == 'Tomcat02'. First ensure global P95 values for each (Tomcat02, kpi_name) are taken from the full series. Then, filter metric rows to timestamp within 2021-03-24 14:15:00 → 2021-03-24 14:24:00 (UTC+8). For each (kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count (rows with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8), max_value (in the window), p95_value, and max_over_p95 (max_value / p95_value; if p95==0 set to NULL). Return the top 10 kpi_name rows ordered by max_over_p95 descending, with columns: kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value, p95_value, max_over_p95. Limit output to 10 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected Tomcat02 metrics at selected minutes (14:16,14:20,14:21,14:22,14:24,14:26). Results show relatively few breaches vs. global P95: the largest relative spike was Tomcat thread count at 14:24 (max_over_p95 ≈ 1.36). Trace analysis earlier revealed a strong trace.self.duration_mean anomaly on Tomcat02 at 2021-03-24T14:20:00+08:00 (max_over_p95 ≈ 2.8), and Tomcat02 produced the earliest Tomcat error_log at 2021-03-24T14:21:20+08:00. Error log and log.error_count spikes peak around 14:21–14:26 across Tomcat nodes (Tomcat02 first to log an error). MySQL/Redis show widespread low-to-moderate anomalies from 14:00 onward (likely background), while trace+log timing points to a service-level latency/failure starting ~14:20 that affected Tomcat services. At this stage we have strong evidence that Tomcat02 exhibited the earliest and most significant downstream duration anomaly (14:20) followed by error logs (14:21), and resource metrics show thread growth at 14:24; however we need to confirm whether Tomcat02 experienced a sustained fault (consecutive anomalous minutes) in request-related KPIs (Requests MaxTime/ErrorCount/ProcessingTime) to mark a fault and determine the exact root-cause reason (e.g., thread exhaustion, high CPU, JVM OOM, or backend DB latency).",
